            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01DobDnrRwnnAz84t9nmpCUE\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01DBeVDkmazvnJSK4WZqTvSc\",\"name\":\"extract\",\"input\":{\"text\":\"I love that you've quantified the time savings—7.5 hours a week is powerful and concrete. That's real value hosts can feel immediately.\\n\\nHere's what I'm sensing though: we know *what* changes (8 hours → 30 min), but we're missing the *why it actually works*. Right now \\\"AI matching\\\" could describe a dozen other platforms. \\n\\nLet me ask you this: **Walk me through what ACTUALLY happens when a host uses Friend of the Pod.** Not the features—the real process. Like, a host logs in, they're looking for a guest for their next episode. What's the first thing they do? What does your AI see that they wouldn't see manually? Why does it catch the 5% of relevant pitches when hosts are drowning in the 95% noise?\\n\\nI'm asking because the real differentiator isn't \\\"we have filters\\\"—it's *how* you filter differently. That's what makes hosts choose you over just hiring an assistant or using Gmail rules.\",\"examples\":[\"Example: 'A host tells us their show is about B2B SaaS. Our AI doesn't just match keywords—it analyzes guest podcasts to find people whose *audience* overlaps with B2B founders, not just people who talk about SaaS. That's why we catch the 5%.'\",\"Example: 'Hosts get bombarded because they're on public lists. Our AI learns which *types* of guests have historically led to higher engagement on their show, then actively filters out the rest. It's predictive, not just reactive.'\"],\"conclusion\":\"Once we nail this, you'll have a real mechanism—something hosts can't get anywhere else. That's what turns 'we save you time' into 'we're the only ones who actually understand your show.'\"}}],\"stop_reason\":\"tool_use\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":2245,\"cache_creation