            "size": 1860,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_01LqSdxZAnsYWuAxbiCGwFPq\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01TXtsKcWHTWMyWN7pM8uhgW\",\"name\":\"extract\",\"input\":{\"text\":\"I love the proprietary angle—training your models on *actual successful pitches* is a real differentiator that most competitors don't have. That's smart.\\n\\nBut here's what I'm missing: **What actually changes for the podcast host?** Right now I know *how* you filter, but not *what they get* as a result.\\n\\nWalk me through this: A host uses Friend of the Pod. What's different about their week? Their show? Their business? Are we talking about:\\n- Reclaiming 5-10 hours per week that they used to spend sifting through garbage pitches?\\n- Getting guests that actually drive downloads or engagement?\\n- Reducing the mental load of saying \\\"no\\\" to 50 bad pitches?\\n- Something else entirely?\\n\\nThe reason I'm asking: Your filters and AI are the *mechanism*, but the transformation is what makes someone actually *want* to buy. Let's nail that down so we can make this irresistible.\",\"examples\":[\"Example: 'Hosts save 8 hours/week on guest vetting and can focus on content strategy instead'\",\"Example: 'Hosts get 3-5 qualified guest pitches per week instead of 50 low-quality ones, so their acceptance rate goes from 2% to 40%'\",\"Example: 'Hosts book guests that are proven to drive 15-20% higher engagement based on audience alignment'\"],\"conclusion\":\"You've got the *what* and the *how*—now let's crystallize the *so what*. That's where the magic happens for your marketing.\\\"\"}}],\"stop_reason\":\"tool_use\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":2242,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":410,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
