          "headersSize": 573,
          "httpVersion": "HTTP/1.1",
          "method": "POST",
          "postData": {
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "params": [],
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5\",\"temperature\":0,\"top_k\":-1,\"stream\":false,\"max_tokens\":2048,\"tools\":[{\"name\":\"extract\",\"description\":\"A function available to call.\",\"input_schema\":{\"type\":\"object\",\"properties\":{\"text\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"description\":\"A simple message or question\"},\"examples\":{\"type\":\"array\",\"items\":{\"type\":\"string\"},\"description\":\"OPTIONAL: List of examples to help the user understand\"},\"conclusion\":{\"type\":\"string\",\"description\":\"OPTIONAL: Conclusion text to include after examples\"}},\"required\":[\"text\"],\"additionalProperties\":false,\"$schema\":\"http://json-schema.org/draft-07/schema#\"}}],\"tool_choice\":{\"type\":\"tool\",\"name\":\"extract\"},\"thinking\":{\"type\":\"disabled\"},\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"\\n    # Brainstorming Agent Core\\n\\nWarm, encouraging marketing consultant. Patient when they're figuring things out.\\n\\n## Question Structure\\n1. Context: Why asking now (reference previous answers)\\n2. The Ask: Specific info needed\\n3. Examples: 2-3 concrete, diverse examples\\n4. Encouragement: Make it doable\\n\\n## When Answer Is Weak (QA said fail)\\n1. Acknowledge the good\\n2. Identify specific gap (use QA reasoning)\\n3. Ask targeted follow-up\\n4. Provide examples\\n\\n## Progression\\n- First answer: Accept high-level\\n- Second: Push for specificity\\n- Third: Dig for insight\\n\\nOutput: `{ text: string, examples?: string[], conclusion?: string }`\\n\\n    \\n    # Brainstorming: Social Proof\\n\\nCredibility = testimonials OR founder story OR track record OR credentials OR proof\\n\\n## Hormozi Proof Hierarchy\\n**High-impact**: Quantified results, case studies, volume, authority\\n**Medium-impact**: Generic testimonials, credentials, years\\n**Low-impact**: Self-reported, vague numbers\\n\\n## For Early-Stage (No Testimonials)\\nFounder credibility, personal transformation, research/process, community size = valid proof\\n\\n## Key Probes\\n- \\\"No testimonials\\\" → Ask about background, personal results, beta users, research\\n- Generic praise → Push for numbers, timeline, transformation\\n- Too much proof → Select most compelling 2-3\\n\\n## Edge Cases\\n- Privacy/NDA → Industry descriptors OK\\n- Pre-launch → Founder story CRITICAL\\n\\n    \\n    <current_topic>socialProof</current_topic>\\n    \\n    <their_answer>Hosts book guests that are proven to drive 15-20% higher engagement</their_answer>\\n    \\n    <qa_evaluation>\\n    Success: false\\n    Reasoning: The answer fails on multiple criteria:\\n\\n1. **Specific** - FAIL: \\\"Hosts book guests\\\" is vague. Which guests? What books? What platform/medium? This could describe thousands of podcasts, YouTube channels, or media outlets.\\n\\n2. **Actionable** - FAIL: Can't write marketing copy from this. The claim lacks the details needed to understand the actual value proposition or differentiation.\\n\\n3. **Authentic** - PARTIAL: The 15-20% engagement lift is quantified, which is good, but the claim itself feels like a marketing statement without supporting evidence or context.\\n\\n4. **Insightful** - FAIL: Doesn't demonstrate understanding of *why* these guests drive engagement or *who* the audience is. No insight into the business model, guest selection criteria, or audience dynamics.\\n\\n**Core issue**: This reads like a marketing claim (\\\"proven to drive 15-20%\\\") without the social proof to back it up. Where's the evidence? How was this measured? What's the baseline? Who are these \\\"proven\\\" guests? This needs either: specific case studies with numbers, founder credibility/background, or quantified results from actual clients/episodes.\\n\\nThe answer needs to move from claiming proof to *showing* proof.\\n    </qa_evaluation>\\n    \\n    <chat_history>\\n        <chat-history>\\n  <message>\\n    assistant: \\\"What is your business?\\\"\\n  </message>\\n  <message>\\n    human: \\\"Friend of the Pod is a podcast matchmaking service.\\\\n            We help both sides: hosts get great content, guests get exposure,\\\\n            and we're the only platform that does this at scale.\\\\n            We solve the \\\\\\\"needle in a haystack\\\\\\\" problem: hosts spend hours\\\\n            finding guests. We do it in minutes with AI-powered filtering.\\\"\\n  </message>\\n  <message>\\n    assistant: \\\"That's awesome! And what about your audience?\\\"\\n  </message>\\n  <message>\\n    human: \\\"\\\\n        My target audience is podcast hosts with large audiences.\\\\n        They want to find guests that are a good fit for their show,\\\\n        but they're bombarded with messages from low-quality, spammy guests\\\\n        who don't add value to their shows.\\\\n    \\\"\\n  </message>\\n  <message>\\n    assistant: \\\"That's awesome! And what about your solution?\\\"\\n  </message>\\n  <message>\\n    human: \\\"Friend of the Pod has over 100+ filters to find the perfect guest for your show.\\\\n                We use AI to match hosts and guests based on their content, audience, and goals.\\\\n                We also use AI to match hosts and guests based on their content, audience, and goals.\\\\n                But what sets us apart is that we've trained proprietary models on messages that \\\\n                successful podcast hosts receive. We use this data to filter out pitches that \\\\n                are predicted to not be a good fit for your show.\\\\n            \\\"\\n  </message>\\n  <message>\\n    assistant: \\\"{\\\\n  \\\\\\\"text\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"You've got a really compelling product here—Friend of the Pod solves a genuine pain point for podcast hosts (the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"needle in a haystack\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" problem), and your AI-powered matching with proprietary models trained on successful pitches is genuinely differentiated.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nNow, here's the thing: when a busy podcast host with a large audience is deciding whether to trust your platform, they're going to ask themselves, \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Has this actually worked for people like me?\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThat's where social proof comes in. Right now, we don't have that story yet, and that's totally okay—but we need to build it.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nSo I'm curious: **What proof do you have right now that Friend of the Pod actually delivers results?** This could be:\\\\\\\\n- Beta users or early testers who've found great guests\\\\\\\\n- Your own experience (did you test this yourself first?)\\\\\\\\n- Metrics from your matching algorithm (accuracy rates, match quality)\\\\\\\\n- Feedback from hosts or guests who've used it\\\\\\\\n- Or maybe you're pre-launch and building this proof right now?\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nI'm asking because the type of proof you have will shape how we position this to your target audience.\\\\\\\",\\\\n  \\\\\\\"examples\\\\\\\": [\\\\n    \\\\\\\"A podcast host who used Friend of the Pod and booked 3 high-quality guests in one week (vs. their usual 2-3 per month)\\\\\\\",\\\\n    \\\\\\\"Your own story: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"I spent 40 hours manually finding guests for my show. I built Friend of the Pod to solve that. Now I do it in 15 minutes.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\",\\\\n    \\\\\\\"Early metrics: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Our AI correctly predicted guest fit 87% of the time, vs. industry average of 60%\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\"\\\\n  ],\\\\n  \\\\\\\"conclusion\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"Whatever stage you're at, we can build credible proof. The key is being specific about what you *do* have, so we can amplify it in a way that resonates with hosts who are tired of spam pitches.\\\\\\\"\\\\n}\\\"\\n  </message>\\n  <message>\\n    human: \\\"Hosts book guests that are proven to drive 15-20% higher engagement\\\"\\n  </message>\\n</chat-history>\\n    </chat_history>\\n    \\n    <task>\\n    Their answer isn't GREAT yet. Ask a specific follow-up that addresses \\n    the weakness identified in the QA evaluation.\\n    \\n    Be constructive and encouraging:\\n    1. Acknowledge what was good\\n    2. Identify the specific gap\\n    3. Ask targeted follow-up\\n    4. Provide examples\\n    \\n    Output JSON: {\\n      \\\"text\\\": \\\"Your clarifying question\\\",\\n      \\\"examples\\\": [\\\"Guiding example 1\\\", \\\"Example 2\\\"],\\n      \\\"conclusion\\\": \\\"Encouraging restatement\\\"\\n    }\\n    </task>\\n  \"}]}"
          },
          "queryString": [],
          "url": "https://api.anthropic.com/v1/messages"
        },
        "response": {
          "bodySize": 1885,
          "content": {
            "mimeType": "application/json",
            "size": 1885,
            "text": "{\"model\":\"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001\",\"id\":\"msg_018J21iJvu16LiNt68afSzgP\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01WmRr9j4VRHgMSxhaJy96x3\",\"name\":\"extract\",\"input\":{\"text\":\"Their answer isn't GREAT yet. Ask a specific follow-up that addresses the weakness identified in the QA evaluation.\\n\\nBe constructive and encouraging:\\n1. Acknowledge what was good\\n2. Identify the specific gap\\n3. Ask targeted follow-up\\n4. Provide examples\\n\\nOutput JSON: {\\n  \\\"text\\\": \\\"Your clarifying question\\\",\\n  \\\"examples\\\": [\\\"Guiding example 1\\\", \\\"Example 2\\\"],\\n  \\\"conclusion\\\": \\\"Encouraging restatement\\\"\\n}\",\"examples\":[\"A podcast host used Friend of the Pod to book a guest in their niche (e.g., a marketing expert for a B2B podcast). That episode got 15-20% more downloads/listens than their average episode, and they attributed it directly to the guest quality.\",\"You tested this yourself: You used your own matching algorithm to book 5 guests for a show, measured engagement on those episodes vs. your baseline, and saw a 15-20% lift on average.\",\"You have data from beta users: 'Of the 12 hosts who used Friend of the Pod in our beta, 8 reported that their matched guests drove higher engagement than their typical guest bookings.'\"],\"conclusion\":\"You've got the *number* (15-20% is great!), but we need the *story* behind it. Once we know where this comes from—whether it's your own testing, beta user feedback, or case studies—we can turn it into something that actually convinces other hosts to trust you. That specificity is what separates a marketing claim from real proof.\"}}],\"stop_reason\":\"tool_use\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":2516,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":0,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0},\"output_tokens\":400,\"service_tier\":\"standard\"}}"
          },
